Tip:
Uses of electroplating
Electroplating has a wide variety of uses. Household objects like cutlery and
cooking utensils are electroplated with metals to stop them corroding. The
metals used for protection are unreactive and don’t corrode easily. Jewellery
and decorative items are often electroplated with metals like gold or silver.
This improves the appearance of the jewellery, making it shiny and attractive.

Practice Questions — Fact Recall
Transition Metals
That most metals are transition metals, and that they are found in the middle of the periodic table.
That most transition metals have high melting points and densities.
How the uses of gold and copper are related to their properties.
That many transition elements and transition element compounds make good catalysts.
That transition metal compounds are often colourful due to the transition metal ion they contain.
Alloys
That pure metals are too weak for many uses so alloys are used as they are harder and stronger.
That alloys are harder and stronger than pure metals because the layers of metal ions in an alloy
cannot slide over each other as easily as in a pure metal.
That iron is too soft and bendy for most uses so is often alloyed to make steel,
which is harder and stronger.
That alloys can be made to have certain properties for a specic purpose.
How the properties of copper, gold and aluminium alloys make them suitable for their uses.
Corrosion
That corrosion is when metals are oxidised in a reaction with oxygen and water.
That iron rusts in the presence of oxygen and water and this is an example of corrosion.
How painting, electroplating or greasing can prevent corrosion by providing a protective barrier.
That a more reactive metal attached to a less reactive metal will act as a sacrice,
corroding rst and so protecting the less reactive metal.
How electroplating can be used to coat a metal object with a different metal, which often improves
the object's appearance and ability to withstand corrosion.
